B.N9=new A.cv("The Sound","Fibrillations sound like 'rain on a tin roof'. PSWs sound like a 'dull thud'.")
B.MI=new A.cv("The Look","Fibrillations are brief spikes (1-5ms) with an initial positive (downward) deflection. PSWs have that same initial positive spike followed by a slow, sweeping negative return.")
B.MP=new A.cv("The Rate","Regular, rhythmic firing between 0.5-10Hz.")
B.N5=new A.cv("The Timeline","These do not appear instantly. Give them 1-3 weeks (or longer) post-injury to develop depending on the distance from the lesion to the muscle.")
B.a6Z=s([B.N9,B.MI,B.MP,B.N5],t.LK)
B.afb=new A.kg("Fibrillations & Positive Sharp Waves","These represent spontaneous muscle fiber discharges, meaning the fiber lost its nerve supply. This is your classic hallmark of active denervation seen in radiculopathy, neuropathy, or motor neuron disease.","jjUZMf8_B1k",B.a6Z)
B.MS=new A.cv("Grade 0","A perfectly clean baseline. None present.")
B.MX=new A.cv("Grade 1+","Persistent single trains in just 2-3 areas. You have to hunt for them.")
B.MN=new A.cv("Grade 2+","A moderate number of potentials found in 3 or more areas.")
B.ME=new A.cv("Grade 3+","Many potentials firing simultaneously in all sampled areas.")
B.MH=new A.cv("Grade 4+","A full 'interference pattern' of spontaneous activity. The screen is completely obliterated by denervation.")
B.a0J=s([B.MS,B.MX,B.MN,B.ME,B.MH],t.LK)
B.af8=new A.kg("Grade 3+ Positive Sharp Waves","When denervation is severe, you don't just see a few blips. You see abundant positive sharp waves filling the screen across multiple muscle areas. This signifies a structurally significant nerve injury.","fT6Lx4rnRNs",B.a0J)
B.MQ=new A.cv("The Sound","An incredibly distinctive, perfectly regular 'machine-like' or 'idling motorcycle' sound.")
B.N_=new A.cv("The Look","Multi-serrated, complex spikes that are completely uniform from discharge to discharge.")
B.N2=new A.cv("The Rate","Typically 5-100Hz. The key is that they are *perfectly* regular, unlike fibs which are semi-rhythmic.")
B.MK=new A.cv("The Mechanism","Ephaptic transmission. One denervated fiber acts as a pacemaker, triggering adjacent denervated fibers in a closed loop.")
B.a0v=s([B.MQ,B.N_,B.N2,B.MK],t.LK)
B.afa=new A.kg("Complex Repetitive Discharges (CRDs)","These sound exactly like a perfectly tuned engine. What you're seeing are individual muscle fibers that are time-linked, firing in an ephaptic loop. We see this in chronic, long-standing neuropathic or myopathic conditions.","UE-UIRDzZ-U",B.a0v)
B.MF=new A.cv("The Sound","A rhythmic grouped bursting. 'Marching soldiers' hitting the pavement.")
B.Na=new A.cv("The Look","Grouped, repetitive discharges of the exact same Motor Unit Action Potential (MUAP).")
B.MJ=new A.cv("The Rate","Interburst frequency is 1-5Hz; intraburst frequency is 5-60Hz.")
B.MC=new A.cv("Key Associations","Radiation plexopathy (very common), Multiple Sclerosis (if facial), Guillain-Barr\xe9, or chronic compressive neuropathy.")
B.a4e=s([B.MF,B.Na,B.MJ,B.MC],t.LK)
B.afe=new A.kg("Myokymic Discharges","Think of an entire motor unit bursting repetitively. It has a very distinct 'marching soldiers' cadence. If you see this in the limbs, strongly consider radiation injury. If you see it in the face, consider MS or a brainstem glioma.","ZClcikXOOaU",B.a4e)
B.N7=new A.cv("The Sound","A 'dive bomber' or a 'revving motorcycle engine'.")
B.MV=new A.cv("The Look","Spiky waves that smoothly grow and then shrink in amplitude while the firing rate speeds up and slows down.")
B.MW=new A.cv("The Rate","Typically 20-150Hz. Remember, the rate actively changes.")
B.N0=new A.cv("Key Pathology","Myotonic dystrophy, myotonia congenita, paramyotonia congenita, and occasionally hyperkalemic periodic paralysis.")
B.a1n=s([B.N7,B.MV,B.MW,B.N0],t.LK)
B.af9=new A.kg("Myotonic Discharges","The classic 'dive bomber.' This is an unstable muscle fiber membrane that repetitively discharges. The defining feature is that it waxes and wanes in both frequency and amplitude.","X29z-QTi0tM",B.a1n)
B.N4=new A.cv("The Sound","Random, large, distant 'pops'. Think of 'corn popping' slowly in a microwave.")
B.N8=new A.cv("The Look","A normal-looking (or reinnervated) MUAP that fires spontaneously.")
B.N1=new A.cv("The Rate","Very slow and highly irregular (0.1-10Hz).")
B.MG=new A.cv("Significance","Hallmark of motor neuron irritability (ALS). However, isolated fasciculations in normal muscle are often benign (caffeine, stress, exercise).")
B.a_Z=s([B.N4,B.N8,B.N1,B.MG],t.LK)
B.afc=new A.kg("Fasciculations","This is simply an entire motor unit deciding to fire randomly on its own. While it can be a benign finding, if you see it alongside fibs/PSWs and chronic reinnervation, you need to think ALS.","u0v4tSZq-Fc",B.a_Z)
B.a5P=s([B.afb,B.af8,B.afa,B.afe,B.af9,B.afc],t.ND)
