B.a8S=new A.ao("S2","Severe Pathology: Ulnar Motor -- distance 300mm, proximal latency 12.8ms, distal latency 2.8ms. Step 1: Subtract (12.8 - 2.8 = 10.0ms). Step 2: Divide (300 / 10.0 = 30 m/s). This velocity has crashed into the 30s -- a severe primary demyelinating neuropathy.",t.q)
B.a8T=new A.ao("Q3","Which fibers are you evaluating during a standard Sural SNAP study? -- Answer: Large, myelinated A-beta fibers. Standard EDX machines only resolve the massive A-alpha and A-beta fibers. We are completely blind to small A-delta and C fibers.",t.q)
B.a8U=new A.ao("Q8","What is the key difference between Seddon's and Sunderland's classification? -- Answer: Seddon uses 3 categories by severity; Sunderland uses 5 grades based on specific anatomical structures damaged.",t.q)
B.a8V=new A.ao("1","Resting State (-70mV): The nerve is negatively charged. Actively maintained by the Na+/K+ ATPase pump, which burns ATP to push 3 Na+ out for every 2 K+ in. The nerve is a loaded spring.",t.q)
B.a8W=new A.ao("5","Hyperpolarization (Overshoot): K+ channels are slightly slow to close, allowing too much positive charge to escape. Potential briefly drops below -70mV before resting state restores.",t.q)
B.a8X=new A.ao("Q5","What EMG finding would you expect in an acute axonal neuropathy (<2 weeks)? -- Answer: Reduced recruitment with NO spontaneous activity yet. Fibrillations take 2-3 weeks to appear.",t.q)
B.a8Y=new A.ao("Q3","What NCS finding indicates axonal loss rather than demyelination? -- Answer: Reduced CMAP amplitude with normal/near-normal conduction velocity.",t.q)
B.a8Z=new A.ao("1","Common Mode Rejection: A differential amplifier's brilliant ability to subtract out identical electrical noise (like 60Hz hum) present at both the Active and Reference electrodes, leaving only the biological nerve signal.",t.q)
B.a9_=new A.ao("Q1","What is the primary pathological difference between demyelinating and axonal neuropathies? -- Answer: Demyelinating affects myelin (slowed velocity, conduction blocks); axonal affects the axon itself (reduced amplitudes, fibrillations on EMG).",t.q)
B.a90=new A.ao("III","Endoneurium disrupted, Perineurium intact. Poor-to-fair recovery. Regenerating sprouts may enter wrong tubes causing aberrant reinnervation.",t.q)
B.a91=new A.ao("9","Anode: The positive (red) pole. If placed between the cathode and recording electrodes, it can cause 'anodal block'.",t.q)
B.a92=new A.ao("3","Giant Motor Units: Over months, surviving nerves sprout tiny branches to 'adopt' the orphaned muscle fibers. When this motor unit fires, it now controls far more muscle fibers than normal, resulting in a massively tall, wide waveform (Chronic Reinnervation).",t.q)
B.a93=new A.ao("4","Repolarization (Restoring): Na+ channels snap shut (inactivation), K+ channels open. K+ rushes out, dropping internal charge back toward negative.",t.q)
B.a94=new A.ao("1","Fibrillation Potentials & Positive Sharp Waves: These indicate active, ongoing denervation. The muscle fiber is crying out for a nerve. They take 2-3 weeks to appear after an injury.",t.q)
B.a95=new A.ao("I","Myelin damage only (= Neurapraxia). Complete recovery in days to weeks.",t.q)
B.a96=new A.ao("Q1","A technician performs NCS on a patient with icy cold hands from walking outside. What pattern does this mimic? -- Answer: A primary demyelinating neuropathy. Cold temperatures slow conduction velocity and prolong latencies, perfectly mirroring demyelination. It also paradoxically increases amplitude.",t.q)
B.a97=new A.ao("Q6","What pathophysiological mechanism causes conduction block? -- Answer: Severe focal demyelination prevents action potential propagation despite intact axons. Reversible with remyelination.",t.q)
B.a98=new A.ao("V","Complete nerve transection (= Neurotmesis). No spontaneous recovery. Requires surgical intervention.",t.q)
B.a99=new A.ao("2","Fasciculations: Spontaneous firing of an entire motor unit. Often benign, but if seen with denervation, highly concerning for Anterior Horn Cell disease (ALS).",t.q)
B.a9a=new A.ao("5","Phase Cancellation: In sensory studies, fast fibers arrive at the electrode early (creating an upward wave), and slower fibers arrive later (creating a downward wave). These opposite waves smash into each other and cancel each other out, artificially reducing the total amplitude the machine reads.",t.q)
B.a9b=new A.ao("Q6","Why do we subtract Distal Latency from Proximal Latency when calculating CV? -- Answer: To eliminate the time spent crossing the Neuromuscular Junction. The NMJ chemical transmission is slow. Subtracting latencies isolates pure nerve travel time so velocity isn't artificially slow.",t.q)
B.a9c=new A.ao("2","Volume Conduction: The passive spread of electrical current through bodily tissues and fluids, much like ripples in a pond. This allows muscles from far away to contaminate your recording.",t.q)
B.a9d=new A.ao("3","Depolarization (+30mV): Na+ floods into the cell, rapidly shifting internal charge from negative to positive. This is the all-or-none action potential spike we record on screen.",t.q)
B.a9e=new A.ao("8","Cathode: The active (black) pole of the stimulator where depolarization of the nerve actually begins. Must always be aimed toward recording electrodes.",t.q)
B.a9f=new A.ao("11","Amplitude: The height (mV) of the waveform, representing the total number of axons firing.",t.q)
B.a9g=new A.ao("S1","Normal Benchmark: Median Motor -- distance 250mm, proximal latency 8.5ms, distal latency 3.5ms. Step 1: Subtract latencies (8.5 - 3.5 = 5.0ms). Step 2: Divide (250 / 5.0 = 50 m/s). This is a perfectly normal conduction velocity.",t.q)
B.a9h=new A.ao("3","Near-field Potential: An electrical signal recorded by an electrode located very close to the biological generator (e.g., standard sensory or motor responses). The voltage changes dynamically as the signal moves.",t.q)
B.a9i=new A.ao("Q2","In a demyelinating neuropathy, what is the most characteristic NCS finding? -- Answer: Slowed conduction velocity with conduction blocks and temporal dispersion.",t.q)
B.a9j=new A.ao("Q4","A patient presents 24 hours after a knife wound severed their median nerve at the elbow. What will the distal CMAP amplitude look like? -- Answer: Perfectly normal. Wallerian degeneration takes 3-5 days (motor) to complete. The distal axon remains electrically viable for several days.",t.q)
B.a9k=new A.ao("10","Latency: The time (ms) from stimulus to the initial onset of the waveform.",t.q)
B.a9l=new A.ao("II","Axon severed, Endoneurium intact (= Axonotmesis). Good-to-excellent recovery at 1mm/day over months.",t.q)
B.a9m=new A.ao("6","H-Reflex: An electrical analog of the tendon monosynaptic reflex. Bypasses the muscle spindle.",t.q)
B.a9n=new A.ao("Q4","What are the three progressive stages of compression neuropathy? -- Answer: Ischemia (reversible) -> Demyelination (conduction block) -> Axonal Loss (Wallerian degeneration).",t.q)
B.a9o=new A.ao("Q9","Peripheral nerves regenerate at approximately what rate? -- Answer: 1 millimeter per day (approximately 1 inch per month). Distance to target determines recovery timeline.",t.q)
B.a9p=new A.ao("2","Threshold (-55mV): When stimulus pushes charge to -55mV, voltage-gated Na+ channels suddenly pop open. An explosive chain reaction begins.",t.q)
B.a9q=new A.ao("IV","Perineurium disrupted, Epineurium intact. Very poor recovery. Neuroma-in-continuity forms, mechanically blocking regrowth.",t.q)
B.a9r=new A.ao("4","Far-field Potential: An electrical signal recorded at a massive distance from the generator. Because it is so far away, the voltage change hits all recording electrodes instantaneously at exactly the same time. The massive stimulus artifact is a far-field potential.",t.q)
B.a9s=new A.ao("Q5","To declare Conduction Block, what must happen to the proximal CMAP compared to distal? -- Answer: Amplitude must drop >50% with minimal temporal dispersion. A sudden massive drop proves the signal hit a focal blockade of demyelination. If it spreads widely, that is dispersion, not block.",t.q)
B.a9t=new A.ao("7","Temporal Dispersion: The broadening of a waveform due to fibers conducting at different speeds, common in demyelination.",t.q)
B.a9u=new A.ao("Q2","You stimulate the ulnar nerve at the wrist, but note the initial deflection is a sharp positive (downward) dip. What is the cause? -- Answer: The G1 (Active) electrode is not placed over the true motor endpoint. It records the approaching wavefront as volume conduction before the muscle fully depolarizes under it.",t.q)
B.a9v=new A.ao("Q7","A diabetic patient has reduced sural/superficial peroneal SNAPs but normal median/ulnar SNAPs. What pattern? -- Answer: Length-dependent sensory polyneuropathy (stocking-glove). Longest nerves affected first.",t.q)
B.a9w=new A.nJ(B.jm,B.jm,A.ae("nJ<n,n>"))
