B.aeb=new A.bz("The Origin","Arises solely from the medial cord of the brachial plexus, carrying fibers predominantly from C8 and T1.",!1)
B.aec=new A.bz("The Origin","Originates from the posterior cord alongside the radial nerve (C5-C6).",!1)
B.aed=new A.bz("The Origin","Arises from the anterior divisions of the lumbar plexus (L2-L4).",!1)
B.aee=new A.bz("The Split","Immediately after surviving the fibular neck, it splits into the Superficial and Deep branches.",!1)
B.aef=new A.bz("The Cubital Tunnel","Passes directly behind the medial epicondyle of the humerus, trapped under Osborne's ligament. This is the 'funny bone'. Bending the elbow stretches the nerve tightly over the bone here, making it the second most common site of nerve compression.",!0)
B.aeg=new A.bz("The Spiral Groove","Winds tightly around the posterior shaft of the humerus in the 'spiral groove'. It lays directly against the bare bone here. Falling asleep with an arm over a park bench ('Saturday Night Palsy') or fracturing the humerus crushes the nerve against the bone.",!0)
B.aeh=new A.bz("The Saphenous Continuation","The final, longest sensory-only branch (the Saphenous Nerve) continues down the inside of the thigh and calf, providing sensation all the way to the inner ankle.",!1)
B.aei=new A.bz("Inguinal Ligament","Slips under the dense inguinal ligament into the thigh. Childbirth or prolonged lithotomy positions can stretch and damage the nerve here.",!0)
B.aej=new A.bz("The Obturator Canal","Must squeeze through a tiny circular window in the pelvis known as the obturator canal to reach the leg. Pelvic fractures or heavy scarring from pelvic surgery can trap the nerve here.",!0)
B.aek=new A.bz("Intrinsic Motor Division","In the palm, it splits. The deep motor branch dives beneath the muscles to supply almost all the small, intrinsic muscles of the hand (interossei, hypothenar eminence, adductor pollicis).",!1)
B.ael=new A.bz("Sensory Transition","Having exhausted its motor fibers, it emerges lateral to the biceps tendon at the elbow as a pure sensory nerve.",!1)
B.aem=new A.bz("The Cubital Fossa","Crosses the front of the elbow joint (cubital fossa), sitting medial to the biceps tendon and brachial artery.",!1)
B.aen=new A.bz("The Origin","Assembles from the posterior divisions of the lumbar plexus (L2-L4), high up in the abdominal vault.",!1)
B.aeo=new A.bz("Deep Calf Muscles","Dives deep under the massive calf muscles (Gastrocnemius and Soleus), providing the critical motor power for pushing off (plantarflexion).",!1)
B.aep=new A.bz("Pelvic Exit","Leaves the protective vault of the pelvis through the greater sciatic foramen.",!1)
B.aeq=new A.bz("Lateral Antebrachial Cutaneous","It changes its name to the Lateral Antebrachial Cutaneous (LAC) nerve, providing feeling to the skin on the lateral (thumb) side of the forearm.",!1)
B.aer=new A.bz("The Origin","The terminal branch of the lateral cord of the brachial plexus (C5-C7).",!1)
B.aes=new A.bz("Surgical Neck Vulnerability","Wraps horizontally around the 'surgical neck' of the upper humerus. If the shoulder pops out of socket (dislocation), the migrating bone stretches and shreds the nerve.",!0)
B.aet=new A.bz("The Great Divide","At the elbow, it splits completely into two distinct paths: the superficial sensory branch and the deep motor branch (the Posterior Interosseous Nerve, or PIN).",!1)
B.aeu=new A.bz("The Tarsal Tunnel","To reach the bottom of the foot, it hooks tightly around the inside ankle bone (medial malleolus) passing under the thick flexor retinaculum. Swelling here causes Tarsal Tunnel Syndrome, leading to burning pain on the sole of the foot.",!0)
B.aev=new A.bz("The Great Divide","Just above the back of the knee (the popliteal fossa), the giant trunk finally unzips into its two terminal components: the Tibial and Common Peroneal nerves.",!1)
B.aew=new A.bz("Quadriceps Starburst","Immediately shatters into numerous deep branches to fire the colossal quadriceps muscles.",!1)
B.aex=new A.bz("Pelvic Journey","Runs along the lateral pelvic wall, largely out of sight.",!1)
B.aey=new A.bz("The Adductor Powerhouse","Splits into anterior and posterior branches to power the massive adductor longus, brevis, and magnus muscles.",!1)
B.aez=new A.bz("Arcade of Frohse (PIN)","The heavy motor branch (PIN) must dive through a tough fibrotic arch in the Supinator muscle known as the Arcade of Frohse. Repetitive twisting motions (mechanics using screwdrivers) can trap the nerve here, causing pure weakness without any numbness.",!0)
B.aeA=new A.bz("Deep Branch (Anterior Tarsal Tunnel)","Dives deep to power the crucial 'dorsiflexor' muscles that pick the foot up. It eventually surfaces at the front of the ankle, passing under the tight extensor retinaculum. Tight shoelaces or heavy boots can compress it here (Anterior Tarsal Tunnel Syndrome).",!0)
B.aeB=new A.bz("Pronator Teres Entrapment","The nerve must dive between the two muscular heads of the Pronator Teres. If this muscle hypertrophies or spasms, it can crush the nerve here, causing 'Pronator Teres Syndrome'.",!0)
B.aeC=new A.bz("Superficial Branch","Travels down the outside of the shin, powering the ankle 'eversion' muscles before spraying out to provide sensation over the broad top of the foot.",!1)
B.aeD=new A.bz("Deltoid Command","Provides massive motor innervation to the entire Deltoid muscle, allowing you to lift your arm outward.",!1)
B.aeE=new A.bz("The Origin","Forms from the convergence of the lateral and medial cords of the brachial plexus in the axilla (C6-T1).",!1)
B.aeF=new A.bz("Posterior Thigh","Descends directly down the midline of the posterior thigh, dispatching thick motor branches to power the hamstrings.",!1)
B.aeG=new A.bz("Fibular Neck Wrap","Swings to the outside of the knee and violently wraps around the bony neck of the fibula. It is shockingly superficial here. Casts, tight knee braces, or simply sleeping awkwardly can crush the nerve against the bone, causing 'Foot Drop'.",!0)
B.aeH=new A.bz("Sensory Division","The superficial branch provides sensation only to the pinky finger and the medial half of the ring finger.",!1)
B.aeI=new A.bz("The Origin (A Meeting of Two)","Uniquely formed when a branch from the tibial nerve (medial sural cutaneous) merges with a branch from the common peroneal nerve.",!1)
B.aeJ=new A.bz("Popliteal Fossa","Crosses behind the knee joint running safely alongside the popliteal artery and vein.",!1)
B.aeK=new A.bz("The AIN Branch","Deep in the forearm, it yields the Anterior Interosseous Nerve (AIN), a pure motor branch that dives to the bone to supply the deep finger and thumb flexors (FDP and FPL).",!1)
B.aeL=new A.bz("Calf Descent","Runs straight down the midline of the back of the calf, traveling safely alongside the small saphenous vein.",!1)
B.aeM=new A.bz("The Origin","The lateral division of the colossal sciatic nerve.",!1)
B.aeN=new A.bz("Lateral Malleolus Landmark","Swings distinctly behind the lateral malleolus (the outside ankle bone). This predictable bony landmark is why we always use the Sural nerve to test for length-dependent neuropathies.",!1)
B.aeO=new A.bz("Guyon's Canal","At the wrist, it bypasses the carpal tunnel entirely. Instead, it runs through a separate superficial bridge called Guyon's Canal, roofed by the volar carpal ligament. Cyclists holding handlebars often crush the nerve here.",!0)
B.aeP=new A.bz("The Origin","The direct medial continuation of the bifurcated sciatic nerve.",!1)
B.aeQ=new A.bz("The Origin","A massive confluence of the sacral plexus, drawing heavy contributions all the way from L4 down to S3.",!1)
B.aeR=new A.bz("Muscle Piercing","Instead of going around, it violently pierces directly through the muscle belly of the Coracobrachialis.",!1)
B.aeS=new A.bz("Piriformis Entrapment","It typically passes just beneath the piriformis muscle deep in the buttocks. In some people, the nerve pierces the muscle. A tight piriformis can fiercely crimp the nerve, causing 'Piriformis Syndrome' (deep buttock pain radiating down the leg).",!0)
B.aeT=new A.bz("Biceps Power","Travels deep to the biceps brachii, providing massive motor innervation to both the biceps and the brachialis muscle beneath it.",!1)
B.aeU=new A.bz("Plantar Division","Successfully through the tunnel, it divides into the Medial and Lateral Plantar nerves, supplying all the intrinsic muscles of the sole and sensory coverage to the bottom of the foot.",!1)
B.aeV=new A.bz("Medial Upper Arm","Travels down the medial aspect of the arm, parallel to the brachial artery, before piercing the medial intermuscular septum to move posteriorly.",!1)
B.aeW=new A.bz("Sensory Patch","Provides a small, highly variable patch of sensation to the skin of the inner thigh.",!1)
B.aeX=new A.bz("Regimental Badge","Terminates by providing a small patch of sensation over the lateral shoulder, exactly where a military patch would sit.",!1)
B.aeY=new A.bz("Dorsal Sensory Path","The superficial sensory branch continues down the forearm under the brachioradialis to safely supply sensation to the back of the hand.",!1)
B.aeZ=new A.bz("The Carpal Tunnel","The ultimate bottleneck. The nerve, along with 9 thick flexor tendons, must pass under the rigid Transverse Carpal Ligament. Any swelling here crushes the nerve against the ligament, resulting in Carpal Tunnel Syndrome\u2014the most common entrapment globally.",!0)
B.af_=new A.bz("Psoas Descent","Travels down through the core meat of the psoas major muscle. A pelvic bleed or tumor can compress the nerve here before it even reaches the leg.",!1)
B.af0=new A.bz("Descent of the Arm","Travels straight down the medial aspect of the humerus running alongside the brachial artery. It gives off absolutely zero branches in the upper arm.",!1)
B.af1=new A.bz("Forearm Entry","Passes between the two heads of the Flexor Carpi Ulnaris (FCU) muscle to enter the anterior compartment of the forearm.",!1)
B.af2=new A.bz("Lateral Emergence","Pierces the lateral intermuscular septum to move to the front of the arm just above the elbow, riding over the lateral epicondyle.",!1)
B.af3=new A.bz("Lateral Foot","Provides absolute sensory coverage to the outer edge of the foot and the pinky toe.",!1)
B.af4=new A.bz("Quadrilateral Space","Dives backward out of the axilla through a tiny square window bordered by the teres major, teres minor, triceps, and humerus.",!1)
B.af5=new A.bz("Hand Terminus","Emerges from the tunnel to supply the crucial thenar muscles (LOAF: Lumbricals 1 & 2, Opponens pollicis, Abductor pollicis brevis, Flexor pollicis brevis) and sensation to the palmar thumb, index, middle, and half of the ring finger.",!1)
B.af6=new A.bz("The Origin","A direct continuation of the posterior cord of the brachial plexus, carrying fibers from all roots (C5-T1).",!1)
B.afg=new A.GS(null,A.ae("GS<hZ,hJ>"))
