a2=A.ci("Posterior Interosseous Nerve Syndrome",a4,s2,"CRITICAL (NCS is characteristically normal)",A.a([A.u(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,g9,h0,f0,f0,h1,f0),A.u(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,h5,h6,f0,f0,h1,f0),A.u(!0,f0,f0,q4,f0,f0,h8,h9,f0,s4,i0,f0),A.u(!0,f0,f0,q4,f0,f0,"Extensor Digitorum Communis (EDC)",x3,f0,h4,i0,f0),A.u(!0,f0,f0,j8,f0,f0,x4,x3,f0,h4,i0,f0),A.u(!1,"Spared (Proximal to PIN)",f0,f0,f0,f0,u9,h9,f0,f0,v2,f0),A.u(!1,"Spared (Innervated before/at entry to arcade)",f0,f0,f0,f0,"Supinator",h9,f0,f0,o8,f0),A.u(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,n9,h9,f0,f0,"C6-C8",f0)],n),"PIN syndrome is a pure motor branch neuropathy of the radial nerve. The hallmark is 'finger drop' with preservation of the Brachioradialis and Supinator (which branch before the PIN enters the Arcade of Frohse). A characteristic finding is Radial Deviation during wrist extension, because the ECRL (Radio-radial) is spared while the ECU (PIN-radial) is weak. Like AIN, the Radial Sensory SNAP is strictly normal, as the PIN carries no cutaneous sensation.",a3,"pin",a5,ae8,ae7,!0,a2,A.a(["PIN syndrome is the radial equivalent of AIN\u2014a pure motor syndrome with strictly Normal Sensation.","Localization Pearl: Preservation of Brachioradialis and Radial Sensory SNAP localizes the lesion distal to the mid-arm/elbow bifurcation.","The 'Radial Deviation' of the wrist is a pathognomonic sign, caused by imbalance between the spared ECRL and the weak ECU.","The most common site of entrapment is the Arcade of Frohse in the supinator muscle."],af3),"Finger Drop without Numbness")
ae7=A.ch(29,"Complete' wrist drop' and numbness on the back of the hand after a long night of sleep",i1,"Woke up after a heavy night of drinking with his arm draped over a hard chair. He found he could not lift his wrist or fingers at all. Significant numbness on the back of the thumb and hand. No neck pain. No trauma.",i4,"Student",i4)
ae8=A.cm("Wrist and fingers hanging in a flexed position (Wrist Drop). No atrophy (hyperacute).","No significant tenderness in the neck or forearm.","Right Brachioradialis reflex 0. Triceps reflex 2+. Left reflexes symmetric.","Full passive ROM. Active extension zero.","Decreased sensation over the radial sensory territory (Snuffbox and dorsal first webspace).","Positive Tinel's sign at the spiral groove of the humerus; Negative Tinel's at the wrist/elbow.","Right Wrist Extension 2/5 (radial deviation only, ECRL partially spared), Finger Extension (EDC) 0/5, Thumb Extension (EPL) 0/5. Brachioradialis 1/5. Supinator 2/5. Triceps strength 5/5. Normal hand intrinsics (APB, ADM, FDI).")
a5=A.a([A.Y("Radial Neuropathy at the Spiral Groove (Saturday Night Palsy)",d9),A.Y(x2,"PIN syndrome spares the Brachioradialis and Supinator and has STRICTLY NORMAL sensation. This case has both BR weakness and snuffbox numbness."),A.Y(n4,"Radiculopathy would typically cause neck pain and involve the triceps; sensory loss would be in the middle finger rather than the first webspace."),A.Y("Brachial Plexopathy (Posterior Cord)","A posterior cord lesion would involve the axillary nerve as well, leading to weak shoulder abduction (Deltoid), which is spared here."),A.Y("Radial Neuropathy at the Axilla","An axillary-level radial lesion (e.g. 'Crutch Palsy') would involve the Triceps, which is spared in this mid-humeral spiral groove injury.")],ae9)
a3=A.a9(["constitutional","Negative.","musculoskeletal","No joint pain.","neurological","Wrist drop and dorsal hand numbness."],af1,af1)
a4=A.a(["None."],af3)
a4=A.ck(A.a(["Ultrasound Humerus: Focal swelling of the radial nerve within the spiral groove.","MRI Arm: Normal; no structural mass or fracture."],af3),a4)
