a5=A.ci("Parsonage-Turner Syndrome",a7,s2,"INDICATED (Look for patchy denervation)",A.a([A.u(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,g9,h0,f0,f0,h1,f0),A.u(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,h5,h6,f0,f0,h1,f0),A.u(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,h8,h9,f0,f0,i0,f0),A.u(!0,f0,f0,q4,f0,f0,r7,f0,f0,h4,f0,f0),A.u(!0,f0,f0,q4,f0,f0,y3,f0,f0,h4,f0,f0),A.u(!0,f0,f0,j8,f0,f0,r9,u8,f0,h4,v2,f0),A.u(!1,f0,f0,k6,f0,f0,y4,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0)],n),"Neuralgic Amyotrophy (PTS) typically presents with a 'pain-weakness sequence': severe, deep-seated shoulder pain that lasts days to weeks, followed by patchy weakness and atrophy in the shoulder girdle. EMG confirms multifocal, patchy denervation (Fibs/PSWs) and normal paraspinals, localizing the lesion as post-ganglionic.",a6,"parsonage",a8,ae8,ae7,!0,a5,A.a(["Parsonage-Turner Syndrome (Neuralgic Amyotrophy) is an idiopathic inflammatory plexitis/neuropathy.","The hallmark is 'patchy' involvement of the brachial plexus, often affecting individual nerves (Long thoracic, Axillary, Suprascapular) rather than traditional trunks or cords.","Normal Cervical Paraspinal EMG identifies the lesion as post-ganglionic (at the plexus or nerve level), ruling out radiculopathy."],af3),"Extreme Shoulder Pain Followed by Weakness")
ae7=A.ch(34,"Tingling and burning pain on the back of the right thumb and index finger",d5,"Develop symptoms after wearing tight-fitting handcuffs during a training exercise 2 weeks ago. The pain is constant and worsened by wrist movement or wearing a tight watch. No weakness in the hand or arm. No neck pain.",i4,"Security Officer",i4)
ae8=A.cm("Mild redness over the radial aspect of the wrist. No atrophy.","Extreme tenderness over the superficial radial nerve as it emerges from under the Brachioradialis tendon (approximately 8cm proximal to the radial styloid).","2+ and symmetric throughout. Brachioradialis reflex normal.",v3,"Decreased sensation (hypesthesia) and burning (allodynia) over the dorsal first webspace and the back of the thumb.","Highly positive Tinel's sign at the radial wrist; Negative Finkelstein's test (rules out De Quervain's).","5/5 strength in ALL muscle groups including wrist/finger extension, brachioradialis, and hand intrinsics.")
a8=A.a([A.Y("Wartenberg's Syndrome (Cheiralgia Paresthetica)",d9),A.Y("De Quervain's Tenosynovitis","A tendonitis causing pain with thumb movement (Positive Finkelstein's), but it does NOT cause neurological numbness or an abnormal SNAP."),A.Y(v8,"Radiculopathy would cause neck pain and involvement of C6 muscles (Biceps/BR) which are normal here. The SNAP is typically spared in a pre-ganglionic root lesion."),A.Y("High Radial Neuropathy","A high radial lesion would cause wrist drop and weakness in the Brachioradialis, which is not present here."),A.Y("First CMC Osteoarthritis","Causes joint pain and stiffness but not neurogenic tingling or sensory loss.")],ae9)
a6=A.a9(["constitutional","Negative.","musculoskeletal","Wrist/Thumb pain.","neurological","Dorsal thumb numbness. **NO WEAKNESS**."],af1,af1)
