b6=A.ci(ab5,b8,s2,"INDICATED (Demyelinating vs Axonal)",A.a([A.u(!0,f0,f0,f0,f0,l3,g9,h0,f0,h4,h1,f0),A.u(!0,ac3,f0,f0,f0,l3,m7,m8,f0,h4,m9,f0),A.u(!0,ac3,f0,f0,f0,l3,r7,z2,f0,h4,"C5",f0),A.u(!0,f0,f0,f0,f0,l3,l5,l6,f0,h4,q3,f0),A.u(!1,"Often spared despite root involvement",f0,f0,f0,f0,"Lumbar Paraspinals (L4)",f0,f0,f0,f0,f0)],n),"Chronic polyradiculoneuropathy (>8 weeks progression) with proximal and distal weakness and generalized areflexia. NCS shows hallmark demyelinating features: prolonged distal latencies, marked velocity slowing (<70% LLN), temporal dispersion, and prolonged F-waves.",b7,"cidp",b9,ae8,ae7,!0,b6,A.a(["CIDP is a chronic demyelinating polyneuropathy characterized by progression >8 weeks.","NCS hallmark: Criteria for demyelination include 1) Prolonged distal latency, 2) Conduction velocity <70% LLN, 3) Abnormal F-waves, and 4) Conduction block or temporal dispersion.","Albuminocytologic dissociation (High protein, normal cell count) in CSF is common.","Proximal weakness is as common as distal weakness in CIDP/GBS because the roots (polyradiculopathy) are involved."],af3),"Chronic Progressive Weakness and Sensory Loss")
ae7=A.ch(55,"1-year history of progressive weakness in the right hand and forearm",i1,"55-year-old male who noticed difficulty with grip strength and occasional dropping of tools. Over the last 6 months, he has developed a significant 'wrist drop' on the right side. No pain, numbness, or tingling. He denies any swallowing or speaking difficulties. His legs are strong and he has no bowel or bladder issues.",ab0,"Gardener",aa9)
ae8=A.cm("Moderate atrophy of the first dorsal interosseous and thenar muscles on the right. No fasciculations observed in the tongue or other limbs.",ac0,"2+ and symmetric throughout. Babinski is negative (flexor). No Hoffmann's sign.",v3,"Entirely normal light touch, pinprick, vibration, and proprioception in all 4 limbs.","Negative Spurling's test. No upper motor neuron (UMN) signs.","Right side: Wrist extension 3/5, Finger extension 3/5, APB 2/5, FDI 3/5. Elbow flexion/extension 5/5. Left side: 5/5 throughout. Lower extremities: 5/5 throughout.")
b9=A.a([A.Y(ab3,d9),A.Y(ab1,"ALS would typically involve UMN signs (brisk reflexes, Babinski) and is rarely focal to one nerve's distribution for a year without spreading or fasciculations; here reflexes are normal and sensory SNAPs are preserved."),A.Y("Lewis-Sumner Syndrome (MADSAM)","MADSAM is a variant of CIDP that involves sensory nerves; here the sensory SNAPs are entirely normal, localizing the lesion to motor fibers only."),A.Y("C7 or C8 Radiculopathy","Radiculopathy would be associated with neck pain and usually spares the distal motor responses (no conduction block); also, paraspinals would be abnormal."),A.Y("Vasculitic Mononeuritis Multiplex","Vasculitis typically causes painful, axonal loss (amplitude drop) and involves sensory nerves (SNAP loss); here it is painless and demyelinating (block).")],ae9)
b7=A.a9(["constitutional",u6,"musculoskeletal","Right hand weakness. No joint pain.","neurological","Pure motor weakness. No numbness or tingling. No cranial nerve symptoms."],af1,af1)
b8=A.a(["Anti-GM1 Ganglioside Antibody: Positive (High Titer)","Creatine Kinase (CK): 250 U/L (Mildly Elevated)","SPEP: Normal"],af3)
b8=A.ck(A.a(["MRI Brachial Plexus: Normal; no masses or root thickening.","Ultrasound Median Nerve: Focal swelling at the mid-forearm (site of conduction block)."],af3),b8)
c0=A.a([A.af(!1,"42.0",ac4,e6,p4,i8),A.af(!1,"38.0",ac4,f1,g1,n7),A.af(!1,"26.0",ac4,f3,f4,f6)],q)
c1=A.a([A.ap(!1,"11.5",f0,g6,w9,p1),A.ap(!0,f8,"63% Conduction Block at Forearm",u7,x0,l1),A.ap(!1,g2,f0,i6,ac5,p1),A.ap(!1,"13.5",f0,aa2,ac6,j5)],o)
c0=A.cl(A.a([A.dh(!1,f0,"3.6",j4,"Median Motor (Left Side)",f0)],m),c1,c0)
b7=A.ci(ab3,b9,s2,"INDICATED (Block vs Axonal Loss)",A.a([A.u(!0,f0,f0,j8,f0,h3,g9,h0,f0,t6,h1,f0),A.u(!0,f0,f0,h2,f0,h3,"Extensor Indicis",h9,f0,h4,i0,f0),A.u(!1,"Sparing of Ulnar territory",f0,f0,f0,f0,h5,h6,f0,f0,h1,f0),A.u(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,r9,u8,f0,f0,v2,f0),A.u(!1,"Sparing rules out root lesion",f0,f0,f0,f0,s5,f0,f0,f0,f0,k6)],n),"Asymmetric, pure motor polyneuropathy. The hallmark is focal conduction block in motor nerves at non-compressive sites (e.g., Median block at forearm) with complete sparing of sensory nerves (Normal SNAPs). Normal reflexes and lack of UMN signs rule out ALS.",b8,"mmn",c0,ae8,ae7,!0,b7,A.a(["Multifocal Motor Neuropathy (MMN) presents with asymmetric, pure motor weakness, often mimicking ALS.","NCS hallmark: Multifocal conduction block in motor nerves outside of common entrapment sites.","Normal sensory SNAPs are essential for diagnosis; their involvement would suggest MADSAM or vasculitis.","Positive anti-GM1 antibodies are found in 50-80% of cases and support the diagnosis.","Unlike ALS, MMN is treatable with IVIG and lacks Upper Motor Neuron signs (no brisk reflexes or Babinski)."],af3),"Asymmetric Hand Weakness and Wrist Drop")
ae7=A.ch(18,"Slowly progressive difficulty walking and frequent ankle sprains",i1,"18-year-old male who has always been 'clumsy' and was never good at sports. In the last 2 years, he noticed his feet appearing 'different' with high arches and toes that are curling. He tires easily when walking long distances and has frequent ankle sprains. No pain or numbness. He mentions his father and paternal aunt have 'funny-looking feet' as well.",i4,"Student","History of frequent ankle sprains")
ae8=A.cm("Marked bilateral Pes Cavus (high arches) and hammer toes. Thinning of the distal leg muscles ('champagne bottle legs' or inverted champagne bottle appearance). No visible fasciculations.","No muscle tenderness. Nerves feel slightly thickened on palpation at the elbows.","Absent (0) Achilles reflexes bilaterally. 1+ Patellar reflexes. 2+ Upper extremity reflexes.",v3,"Symmetric mildly decreased pinprick and vibration in a stocking distribution (to the ankles). Proprioception is normal.","Gait: Mild steppage gait noted. Negative Romberg.","Symmetric distal weakness: Ankle dorsiflexion 4-/5, Eversion 3+/5, Toe extension 3/5. Hand intrinsics 4/5. Proximal strength (Hips/Shoulders) is 5/5.")
c0=A.a([A.Y("Charcot-Marie-Tooth Type 1 (CMT1)",d9),A.Y(ab5,"CIDP is an acquired condition with non-uniform slowing (blocks/dispersion) and typically has a more rapid progression with proximal involvement; here the history is life-long and slowing is uniform."),A.Y("Distal Muscular Dystrophy","Would show myopathic changes on EMG (small units) rather than neurogenic changes; standard NCS velocities would be normal."),A.Y("Friedreich's Ataxia","Would involve gait ataxia, cardiomyopathy, and often diabetes; the primary finding is sensory loss and absent reflexes, but the motor NCS slowing here is more typical of CMT1."),A.Y("Kennedy's Disease","Primarily motor with bulbar involvement and a later onset; CMT1 is more distal/leg predominant and has the characteristic skeletal deformities.")],ae9)
b8=A.a9(["constitutional",u6,"musculoskeletal","High arches and curling toes. Frequent ankle instability.","neurological","Chronic difficulty walking. No hand numbness. No bowel/bladder issues."],af1,af1)
b9=A.a(["Genetic Testing: PMP22 duplication detected.","SPEP: Normal.","HbA1c: 5.2% (Normal)."],af3)
